# API & Server Action rules

Keep handlers **thin** — validate input, call `src/lib/` modules, map errors to action responses.

## Auth

- Every Server Action starts with `requireSalesAccess()` (or `requireSalesAdmin()` for Xero settings) from `src/lib/meavo-auth.ts`.
- API routes are NOT protected by middleware — `src/app/api/quotes/[id]/pdf/route.ts` does its own session + `ToolCardAccess` check; copy that pattern for any new route handler.
- If a cron route is ever added, require `CRON_SECRET` Bearer auth.
- Never import Prisma-backed auth in `src/middleware.ts` (edge) — it uses `src/lib/auth.config.ts` only.

## Validation

- Zod at the boundary: `quoteInputSchema` / `convertInputSchema` (`src/lib/quote-input.ts`), `clientInputSchema` (`src/lib/client-input.ts`). Env vars are read directly from `process.env` (documented in `.env.example`).

## Responses

- Actions return `{ ok: true, id } | { ok: false, error }` (products use `{ error?, success? }` for `useActionState`); user-facing failures are messages, never thrown stack traces.
- Call `revalidatePath()` for every page a write affects (list page + detail page).
- New REST endpoints only for streaming/binary (like the PDF) or auth — mutations stay Server Actions.

## Side effects

- Ops File and Xero exports after conversion never throw — they persist errors on the `Deal` (`sheetSyncError` / `xeroSyncError`); retries via `retryOpsSheetSyncAction` / `retryXeroInvoiceAction`.

## Do NOT

- Put business rules inline in route handlers or actions — they belong in `src/lib/`
- Skip auth on routes exposed to the internet
- Return stack traces to clients in production
